{"doc_urls":["starting.html#-zebraw","starting.html#starting","feature.html#features","feature.html#line-highlighting","feature.html#comment","feature.html#header-and-footer","feature.html#language-tab","feature.html#copyable","feature.html#theme","customization.html#customization","customization.html#inset","customization.html#colors","customization.html#font","customization.html#extend","documentation.html#documentation","example.html#example"],"index":{"documentStore":{"docInfo":{"0":{"body":26,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"1":{"body":22,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"10":{"body":7,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"11":{"body":32,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"12":{"body":23,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"13":{"body":9,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"14":{"body":9,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"15":{"body":0,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"2":{"body":0,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"3":{"body":20,"breadcrumbs":3,"title":2},"4":{"body":35,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"5":{"body":22,"breadcrumbs":3,"title":2},"6":{"body":10,"breadcrumbs":3,"title":2},"7":{"body":21,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"8":{"body":2,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1},"9":{"body":53,"breadcrumbs":2,"title":1}},"docs":{"0":{"body":"Zebraw is a lightweight and fast package for displaying code blocks with line numbers in typst, supporting code line highlighting. The term Zebraw is a combination of zebra and raw , for the highlighted lines will be displayed in the code block like a zebra lines.","breadcrumbs":"Starting » 🦓 Zebraw","id":"0","title":"🦓 Zebraw"},"1":{"body":"Import zebraw package by #import \"@preview/zebraw:0.4.0\": * then follow with #show: zebraw to start using zebraw in the simplest way. To manually display some specific code blocks in zebraw, you can use #zebraw() function:","breadcrumbs":"Starting » Starting","id":"1","title":"Starting"},"10":{"body":"Customize the inset of each line by passing a to the inset parameter:","breadcrumbs":"Customization » Inset","id":"10","title":"Inset"},"11":{"body":"Customize the background color by passing a or an of s to the background-color parameter. Customize the highlight color by passing a to the highlight-color parameter: Customize the comments' background color by passing a to the comment-color parameter: Customize the language tab's background color by passing a to the lang-color parameter.","breadcrumbs":"Customization » Colors","id":"11","title":"Colors"},"12":{"body":"To customize the arguments of comments' font and the language tab's font, pass a dictionary to comment-font-args parameter and lang-font-args parameter. Language tab will be rendered as comments if nothing is passed.","breadcrumbs":"Customization » Font","id":"12","title":"Font"},"13":{"body":"Extend at vertical is enabled at default. When there's header or footer it will be automatically disabled.","breadcrumbs":"Customization » Extend","id":"13","title":"Extend"},"14":{"body":"The default value of most parameters are none for it will use the default value in zebraw-init.","breadcrumbs":"Documentation » Documentation","id":"14","title":"Documentation"},"15":{"body":"","breadcrumbs":"Example » Example","id":"15","title":"Example"},"2":{"body":"","breadcrumbs":"Feature » Features","id":"2","title":"Features"},"3":{"body":"You can highlight specific lines in the code block by passing the highlight-lines parameter to the zebraw function. The highlight-lines parameter can be a single line number or an array of line numbers.","breadcrumbs":"Feature » Line Highlighting","id":"3","title":"Line Highlighting"},"4":{"body":"You can add comments to the highlighted lines by passing an array of line numbers and comments to the highlight-lines parameter. Comments can begin with a flag, which is \">\" by default. You can change the flag by passing the comment-flag parameter to the zebraw function: To disable the flag feature, pass \"\" to the comment-flag parameter (the indentation of the comment will be disabled as well):","breadcrumbs":"Feature » Comment","id":"4","title":"Comment"},"5":{"body":"Usually, the comments passing by a dictionary of line numbers and comments are used to add a header or footer to the code block: Or you can use header and footer parameters to add a header or footer to the code block:","breadcrumbs":"Feature » Header and Footer","id":"5","title":"Header and Footer"},"6":{"body":"If lang is set to true, then there will be a language tab on the top right corner of the code block:","breadcrumbs":"Feature » Language Tab","id":"6","title":"Language Tab"},"7":{"body":"If copyable is set to true, line numbers will not be copied when copying exported code. For comparison: However when a code block is copyable, it won't be able to cross page. Only line numbers will be excluded for being selected.","breadcrumbs":"Feature » Copyable","id":"7","title":"Copyable"},"8":{"body":"PRs are welcome!","breadcrumbs":"Feature » Theme","id":"8","title":"Theme"},"9":{"body":"There are 3 ways to customize code blocks in your document: Manually render some specific blocks by #zebraw() function and passing parameters to it. By passing parameters to #show: zebraw.with() will affect every raw block after the #show rule, except blocks created manually by #zebraw() function. By passing parameters to #show: zebraw-init.with() will affect every raw block after the #show rule, including blocks created manually by #zebraw() function. By using zebraw-init without any parameters, the values will be reset to default.","breadcrumbs":"Customization » Customization","id":"9","title":"Customization"}},"length":16,"save":true},"fields":["title","body","breadcrumbs"],"index":{"body":{"root":{"3":{"df":1,"docs":{"9":{"tf":1.0}}},"a":{"d":{"d":{"df":2,"docs":{"4":{"tf":1.0},"5":{"tf":1.4142135623730951}}},"df":0,"docs":{}},"df":0,"docs":{},"f":{"df":0,"docs":{},"f":{"df":0,"docs":{},"e":{"c":{"df":0,"docs":{},"t":{"df":1,"docs":{"9":{"tf":1.4142135623730951}}}},"df":0,"docs":{}}}},"r":{"df":0,"docs":{},"g":{"df":1,"docs":{"12":{"tf":1.4142135623730951}},"u":{"df":